commendations for practice and policy and suggestions for cultural change.Andrea J. Nichols approaches sex-trafficking-related theories, research, policies, and practice from neoliberal, abolitionist, feminist, criminological, and sociological perspectives. She confronts competing views of the relationship between pornography, prostitution, and sex trafficking, as well as the contribution of weak social institutions and safety nets to the spread of sex trafficking. She also explores the link between identity-based oppression, societal marginalization, and the risk of victimization. She clearly accounts for the role of race, ethnicity, immigrant status, LGBTQ identities, age, sex, and intellectual disability in heightening the risk of trafficking and how social services and the criminal justice and healthcare systems can best respond. This textbook is essential for understanding the mechanics of a pervasive industry and curbing its spread among at-risk populations.Please visit our supplemental materials page (https://cup.columbia.edu/extras/supplement/sex-trafficking-united-states) to find teaching aids, including PowerPoints, access to a test bank, and a sample syllabus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aHuman traffickingzUnited States. 0aProstitutionzUnited States. 0aSex crimeszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Prostitution & Sex Trade.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016z978311063857840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/nich1726240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231542364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231542364.jpg  a978-3-11-063857-8  CUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL